\begin_layout Standard
Imagine that the maximum die temperature of the power amplifier can be is
 150 °C and that the surrounding temperature goes up to 70 °C.
 The maximum output power of the power amplifier equals to 15 W and the
 maximum power of the power ampilifier equals to 25W.
 Then the total junction-to-ambient thermal resistance must be less than
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "key-1"

\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
θ_{ja}=\frac{T_{JMAX}-T_{AMB}}{P_{Q}}=\frac{150-70}{25-15}=8,0\text{º}C/W\label{eq:2-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
T
\begin_inset script subscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
JMAX
\end_layout

\end_inset

is the maximum temperature that the power amplifier can take before shutting
 down.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
T
\begin_inset script subscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
AMB
\end_layout

\end_inset

is the surrounding temperature of the power amplifier.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
P
\begin_inset script subscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Q
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is the quiescent power dissipation of the amplifier.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The thermal resistance of a metal-metal interface when dry equals: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
θ_{jc}=1,2\text{º}C/W\label{eq:2-2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The thermal resistance of the heatsink equals: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
θ_{ca}=θ_{ja}-θ_{jc}=8,0\text{º}C/W-1,2\text{º}C/W=6,8\text{º}C/W\label{eq:2-3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To check whether the calculations are correct, we determine the temperature
 of the junction as a result of the thermal resistance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The maximum average power that the IC will be required to dissipate is approxima
tely 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "key-1"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{d}MAX=\frac{V_{S}^{2}}{2π^{2}R_{L}}+P_{Q}=\frac{18^{2}}{2π^{2}\cdot8}+10=12,05W\label{eq:2-4}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
V
\begin_inset script subscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
S
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is the total power supply voltage across the power amplifier.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
R
\begin_inset script subscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
L
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is the load resistance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
P
\begin_inset script subscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Q
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is the quiescent power dissipation of the amplifier.
 The maximun power of the power amplifier is 25 W and the maximum required
 power is 15 W.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{Q}=25W-15W=10W\label{eq:2-5}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The new maximum die temperature is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
T_{JMAX}=P_{d}MAX\cdotθ_{ja}=12,05\cdot8=96,4\text{º}C\label{eq:2-6}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
96,4 °C is lower than 150 °C and therefore the new junction-to-ambient thermal
 resistance equals to:
